1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:02,480
Today we are exploring the Cover block.

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:08,680
An excellent tool for creating headers, banner-style displays, call-to-actions and much more.

3
00:00:08,680 --> 00:00:14,120
The Cover block allows you to display text and other content on top of an image or video.

4
00:00:14,120 --> 00:00:17,240
In this session we will create two different designs.

5
00:00:17,240 --> 00:00:21,440
But first, let's take a quick look at some of the key features and settings we need to

6
00:00:21,440 --> 00:00:23,480
know before continuing.

7
00:00:23,480 --> 00:00:27,480
The important thing to understand is that the Cover block is a container block that can

8
00:00:27,480 --> 00:00:30,040
hold other blocks within it.

9
00:00:30,040 --> 00:00:34,240
When you add a Cover block to your page, you have the option to upload an image or video

10
00:00:34,240 --> 00:00:36,760
from your computer or Media Library.

11
00:00:36,760 --> 00:00:41,680
You can also select the 'Use Featured Image' option to set the cover as the featured image

12
00:00:41,680 --> 00:00:43,840
of your page or post.

13
00:00:43,840 --> 00:00:48,360
And then you can click on the coloured circles to add an overlay colour to your Cover block

14
00:00:48,360 --> 00:00:53,360
which you can update later in the sidebar settings.

15
00:00:53,360 --> 00:00:56,760
Let's add an image from our Media Library.

16
00:00:56,760 --> 00:01:02,480
It is also worth noting that WordPress automatically adds an overlay colour that complements the

17
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:04,560
image.

18
00:01:04,560 --> 00:01:09,960
Once inserted, select your Cover block in your List View and then use the block toolbar

19
00:01:09,960 --> 00:01:14,720
to change the alignment to full width.

20
00:01:14,720 --> 00:01:20,240
You can also change the content position to top left, middle left or elsewhere.

21
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:25,400
Additionally, you can toggle your Cover block to full height and add a duotone filter if

22
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:27,240
desired.

23
00:01:27,240 --> 00:01:33,240
In the sidebar settings, we have an option to select 'Fixed Background' which creates

24
00:01:33,240 --> 00:01:39,760
a parallax effect.

25
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:44,480
The Repeat Background option is useful when an image isn't the size of the space it

26
00:01:44,480 --> 00:01:45,960
fills.

27
00:01:45,960 --> 00:01:51,640
The focal point picker allows you to identify the most important visual point of an image,

28
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:54,080
especially for mobile viewing.

29
00:01:54,080 --> 00:01:58,000
Also remember to add alt text to describe the purpose of the image for screen readers

30
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,200
and SEO.

31
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:08,720
Below Styles, you can edit the colour overlay and change its opacity to make a darker or

32
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:10,440
lighter.

33
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:16,760
Next, you can also add padding to create more space around the content in your Cover block.

34
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:20,640
Now we can move on to some examples.

35
00:02:20,640 --> 00:02:25,640
In the first example, I wanted to show you how I created the following banner.

36
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:34,040
We can go ahead and add the Cover block and then select an image from our Media Library.

37
00:02:34,040 --> 00:02:41,080
Next I will ensure that I select the Cover block and then change the alignment to full

38
00:02:41,080 --> 00:02:43,120
width.

39
00:02:43,120 --> 00:02:47,880
And then I will change the content position to top middle.

40
00:02:47,880 --> 00:02:50,240
Then we can go ahead and add some text.

41
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:58,120
In this case, I will write 'Explore the mountains' and then change the size of the text to a

42
00:02:58,120 --> 00:03:00,440
custom size.

43
00:03:00,440 --> 00:03:04,200
And for this example, we'll change it to '4 rem.'

44
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:10,920
I'm also going to change the appearance of the text to 'medium'.

45
00:03:10,920 --> 00:03:16,720
To change the alignment of the text, I'm going to wrap the Paragraph block or the text

46
00:03:16,720 --> 00:03:20,880
in a Group block.

47
00:03:20,880 --> 00:03:24,440
And then, deselect 'Inner blocks use content width.'

48
00:03:24,440 --> 00:03:29,000
And once I've done that, I can go ahead and change the alignment of the Group block

49
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,000
to full width.

50
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:37,360
Then I will select the Cover block, open Styles.

51
00:03:37,360 --> 00:03:44,440
Then I will leave my overlay opacity at 50% and then we can add some padding or some

52
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:50,360
space around the content of our block.

53
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:55,600
Now we can close the List View in the sidebar settings and now that the design is finished,

54
00:03:55,600 --> 00:04:01,000
we can also check to see what it will look like on a mobile device.

55
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:05,440
If you did not want your image to be cropped as we see here, you can change the aspect

56
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:06,940
ratio.

57
00:04:06,940 --> 00:04:13,680
To do that, we can return to the page and open up Styles and then scroll down to aspect

58
00:04:13,680 --> 00:04:15,480
ratio.

59
00:04:15,480 --> 00:04:23,160
I will go ahead and select a Classic 3x2 aspect ratio.

60
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:31,680
And now, if we view it on mobile, we will see the image is not cropped.

61
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:37,200
The image scales appropriately and maintains its proportions.

62
00:04:37,200 --> 00:04:42,080
In the next example, I want to show you how I created this cool parallax effect, blending

63
00:04:42,080 --> 00:04:45,840
the two images together.

64
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:53,800
To create this design, I added a Cover block and then selected an image from my Media Library.

65
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:59,160
Once inserted, I selected the Cover block and changed the alignment to full width and

66
00:04:59,160 --> 00:05:03,200
I toggled the block to full height.

67
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:08,760
Then I open the sidebar settings and selected Fixed Background to create the parallax

68
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:09,760
effect.

69
00:05:09,760 --> 00:05:14,400
Then I will click on the three vertical dots of my block tool bar and duplicate.

70
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:20,920
Once the block is duplicated, I will add a new image.

71
00:05:20,920 --> 00:05:30,240
Next I will open up my List View, select both Cover blocks and add them to a Group block.

72
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:34,580
As I want to remove the space between the two images, then I will open up the Styles

73
00:05:34,580 --> 00:05:40,600
of the Group block, make my way to block spacing and change it to zero.

74
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:44,480
Please note, if you don't see the block spacing setting, it might be because of the theme

75
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:46,160
you are using.

76
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:54,080
And then our design is done.

77
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:57,640
And then we can also view it on a smaller screen.

78
00:05:57,640 --> 00:06:03,880
Finally, I want to show you some other designs I created using the Cover block.

79
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:10,400
In this case, I used the Cover block to create this call-to-action for a portfolio website.

80
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:14,920
Also, don't forget to go to the Patterns Directory to find awesome patterns that have

81
00:06:14,920 --> 00:06:18,080
been built with the Cover block.

82
00:06:18,080 --> 00:06:24,640
In the last example, I used one of those header patterns to create a header for my owl sanctuary

83
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:31,600
website with the logo and site title top left and my navigation menu top right.

84
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:35,800
And here we can also view it on mobile.

85
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:40,440
Enjoy using the Cover block and always double check that your designs appear correctly

86
00:06:40,440 --> 00:06:41,680
on smaller screens.

